Local Cricket Scoring Web App - Requirements Specification

1. Purpose & Vision
Build a simple, mobile-first cricket scoring web app for local teams.
No registration required.
Live scoring, spectator view, scorer handoff, and shareable scorecards.

2. Users & Roles
Scorer (Editor): Can score and control the match.
Spectator (Viewer): Can only view the live scoreboard.

3. Platform & UX
Mobile-first responsive design.
Large buttons for one-hand use.
Fast load time on slow networks.
Works on all modern mobile browsers.

4. Match Setup & Configuration
Match name is optional.
Match type default is 'Friendly'.
Overs are required input.
Balls per over default is 6 (editable).
Location / ground is optional.

5. Teams & Players
Create and manage teams.
Select players from any team pool for a match.
Allow guest players.
Easily move players between teams.

6. Scoring & Match Control
Ball-by-ball scoring interface.
Quick buttons for runs and extras.
Auto update score, wickets, overs, and run rate.

7. Scorer Handoff
Generate a scorer transfer link.
New scorer requests control.
Current scorer approves and hands over control.
Prevent multiple scorers editing at the same time.

8. Live Spectator View
Public, read-only live scoreboard.
Auto-updating view.
Sharable spectator link via WhatsApp or copy link.

9. Scoreboard & Export
Live innings scoreboard.
Final match summary.
Export scoreboard as PDF or image.

10. Data & Storage
No user accounts required.
Link-based access for scoring and viewing.
Lightweight backend and browser storage.

11. Security
Separate edit and view access.
Input validation and sanitization.
No personal data beyond player names.

12. Non-Functional Requirements
Free-tier deployable.
Fast and reliable.
Low cost and no paid APIs.

13. Team User Authorization (New Requirement)
Support authorized users for each team.
Allow assignment of user roles: Team Admin, Coach, Manager, Scorer, Umpire.
Umpire role is optional; a match may or may not include an umpire.
Authorized users can manage team players, approve scorer handoff, and access restricted team functions.
Maintain role-based permissions without requiring full user accounts.
Must not alter existing link-based access behavior.

